\begin_layout Standard
The phase between each successive reflection is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Born2002"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\delta=\left(\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}\right)2nl\cos\left(\theta\right)\end{equation}

\end_inset

If both surfaces have reflectance 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, the transmittance function of the entire structure is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T=\frac{(1-R)^{2}}{1+R^{2}-2R\cos\left(\delta\right)}=\frac{1}{1+F\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\delta}{2}\right)},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\frac{4R}{(1-R)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the finesse coefficient.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:etalon-transmittance-function"

\end_inset

 shows the dependence of the transmittance on the phase parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, for various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (or equivalently of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

).
 The maximum transmission occurs when the optical path length difference
 
\begin_inset Formula $2nl\cos(\theta)$
\end_inset

 between each transmitted beam is an integer multiple of the wavelength.
 In the absence of absorption, the reflectance of the structure 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the complement of the transmittance, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R+T=1$
\end_inset

.
 The maximum reflectivity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R_{max}=1-\frac{1}{1+F},\end{equation}

\end_inset

which occurs when the path-length difference is equal to half an odd multiple
 of the wavelength.
\end_layout

