\begin_layout Standard
The wavelength separation between adjacent transmission peaks or free spectral
 range (FSR) of the etalon, 
\begin_inset Formula $Δλ$
\end_inset

, is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta\lambda=\frac{\lambda_{0}^{2}}{2nl\cos(\theta)+\lambda_{0}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $λ_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the central wavelength of the nearest transmission peak.
 The FSR is related to the full-width half-maximum (FWHM) 
\begin_inset Formula $δλ$
\end_inset

 of any one transmission band by a quantity known as the 
\emph on
finesse
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}=\frac{\Delta\lambda}{\delta\lambda}=\frac{\pi}{2\arcsin(1/\sqrt{F})}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Distributed Bragg Reflector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reflecting surfaces (or mirrors) modeled in previous section by a reflectivi
ty parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are realized in practice by a stack of multiple layers of alternating semicondu
ctor materials with varying refractive indices called Distributed Bragg
 Reflector (DBR) (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic-DBR"

\end_inset

).
 The alternating high and low indices, denoted respectively by 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{L}$
\end_inset

, and the semiconductor layer thicknesses satisfy the following condition
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n_{L}l_{L}=n_{H}l_{H}=\frac{\lambda_{c}}{4},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the center wavelength of the high reflectivity region of the structure.
 The two indices 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{r}$
\end_inset

 are, respectively, the left- and right-hand cladding material refractive
 indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principle of operation can be understood as follows.
 Each interface between the two materials contributes a Fresnel reflection.
 For the design wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

, the optical path length difference between reflections from subsequent
 interfaces is half the wavelength; in addition, the reflection coefficients
 for the interfaces have alternating signs.
 Therefore, all reflected components from the interfaces interfere constructivel
y, which results in a strong reflection.
 The reflectivity achieved is determined by the number of layer pairs and
 by the refractive index contrast between the layer materials.
 The reflection bandwidth is determined mainly by the index contrast, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{H}-n_{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

