\begin_layout Standard
In order to analyze the reflection and transmittance of the DBR, we use
 the Transfer Matrix formalism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Macleod2001"

\end_inset

, as is described in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Transfer-Matrix-Method"

\end_inset

Transfer Matrix Method (TMM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A monochromatic electric field of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 propagating in a dielectric medium, assuming a frequency independent dielectric
 function, can be shown to satisfy the following wave equation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla^{2}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r})+\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}(r)}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r})=0,\label{eq:E_wave_eqaution_r}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r},t)=\Re\left\{ \mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r})e^{i\omega t}\right\} ,\]

\end_inset

the speed of light in the dielectric 
\begin_inset Formula $c(r)=c_{0}/n(r)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 being the speed on light in the vacuum and 
\begin_inset Formula $n(r)$
\end_inset

 the location dependent refractive index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A medium consisting of pairs of two different dielectric materials with
 different refraction indices has a growth axis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

, dependent refraction index, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $n(r)=n(z)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:E_wave_eqaution_r"

\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla^{2}\mathbf{E}(\rho,z)+\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}(z)}\mathbf{E}(\rho,z)=0.\label{eq:E_wave_equation_z}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Because of the translational invariance along the in-plane, the solution
 of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:E_wave_equation_z"

\end_inset

 consists of plane waves along the in-plane direction.
 For a given in-plane wave vector 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 (parallel to the dielectric layer plane) we can make the following ansatz
 for the solution 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}_{\mathbf{k}_{t}}=E_{\mathbf{k}_{t},\omega}(z)e^{i\mathbf{k}_{t}\cdot\mathbf{\rho}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:E_wave_equation_z"

\end_inset

 yields the following one-dimensional equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}E_{\mathbf{k}_{t},\omega}(z)}{dz^{2}}+\left(\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}(z)}-k_{t}^{2}\right)E_{\mathbf{k}_{t},\omega}(z)=0.\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation can be solved separately for each layer of the stack.
 The solution for a homogeneous layer with a constant refractive index is
 of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
E_{\mathbf{k}_{t},\omega}(z) & = & E^{+}e^{ik_{z}z}+E^{-}e^{-ik_{z}z},\nonumber \\
k_{z} & = & \sqrt{\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}-\mathbf{k}_{t}^{2}}.\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution is a linear combination of two traveling waves in opposite
 direction along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 axis.
 A non-evanescent wave solution exist only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\omega}{c}>\mathbf{k}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The complex amplitudes of the forward (
\begin_inset Formula $E^{+})$
\end_inset

 and backward (
\begin_inset Formula $E^{-}$
\end_inset

) propagating waves are determined from the boundary conditions at each
 interface between two adjacent layers of the stack.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relation between the two complex amplitudes between two point along
 the propagation direction, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}$
\end_inset

, can be expressed as a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix transfer matrix.
 From here on we assume the non-unique basis for the transfer matrix is
 
\begin_inset Formula $(E^{+},E^{-})$
\end_inset

.
 The transfer matrix takes into account the propagation through the dielectric
 media and the boundary conditions at each interface between two adjacent
 layers.
 The boundary conditions resulting from Maxwell's equations state that tangentia
l components of the electric and magnetic fields are continuous across the
 interface.
 The boundary conditions for the field components can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
D_{\perp1} & =D_{\perp2}\nonumber \\
B_{\perp1} & =B_{\perp2}\nonumber \\
E_{\parallel1} & =E_{\parallel2}\label{eq:62}\\
H_{\parallel1} & =H_{\parallel2}\nonumber \end{align}

\end_inset

For simplicity we assume propagation only in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 direction and normal incidence of the light waves on the dielectric interfaces.
 The boundary conditions for the electric field become
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../AdvancedLab/Figures/Boundary_And_Propagation.png
	lyxscale 60
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Ligth_Propagation_Interface"

\end_inset

Schematic description of (a) light propagation through an interface between
 two adjacent dielectric layers and (b) light propagation in a homogeneous
 medium.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Ligth_Propagation_Interface"

\end_inset

(a)) 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
E_{1}^{+}+E_{1}^{-} & = & E_{2}^{+}+E_{2}^{-}\label{eq:63}\\
n_{2}\left(E_{2}^{+}-E_{2}^{-}\right) & = & n_{1}\left(E_{1}^{+}-E_{1}^{-}\right)\label{eq:64}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The interface transfer matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

, for both linear polarizations of the field, TE and TM, can be written
 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{2}^{+}\\
E_{2}^{-}\end{array}\right)=\frac{1}{2n_{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
n_{2}+n_{1} & n_{2}-n_{1}\\
n_{2}-n_{1} & n_{2}+n_{1}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{1}^{+}\\
E_{1}^{-}\end{array}\right)\equiv M_{i}\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{1}^{+}\\
E_{1}^{-}\end{array}\right)\end{equation}

\end_inset

or a wave propagating from layer 1 to layer 2.
 The in-layer propagation transfer matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{p}$
\end_inset

, which relates different vectors at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the same layer can be written as (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Ligth_Propagation_Interface"

\end_inset

(b))
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{2}^{+}\\
E_{2}^{-}\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
e^{ikl} & 0\\
0 & e^{-ikl}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{1}^{+}\\
E_{1}^{-}\end{array}\right)\equiv M_{p}\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{1}^{+}\\
E_{1}^{-}\end{array}\right),\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\left(\nicefrac{\omega}{c_{0}}\right)n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This amplitude propagation approach can be applied to the entire multilayer
 structure, for which the transfer matrix is simply the multiplication of
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{p}$
\end_inset

 matrices for each boundary and layer
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
M_{DBR}=\prod_{m}M_{i,m}M_{p,m},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the dielectric layer index.
 The explicit relation between the amplitudes of the incident electric field
 in the DBR structure and the transmitted field on the other side can be
 written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{out}^{+}\\
0\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
M_{11} & M_{12}\\
M_{21} & M_{22}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
E_{in}^{+}\\
E_{in}^{-}\end{array}\right).\label{eq:Transfer_Matrix_Formulation}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reflection and transmission coefficients of the entire structure can
 thus be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
r_{DBR} & = & -\frac{M_{21}}{M_{22}}\\
t_{DBR} & = & \frac{\det(M_{DBR})}{M_{22}}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

