\begin_layout Standard
The reflection coefficient can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{DBR}(\lambda)=|r|e^{i\alpha_{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 It can be shown that for a structure containing 
\begin_inset Formula $2N+1$
\end_inset

 layers of high and low refractive indices (as in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic-DBR"

\end_inset

), so that the outermost layers are of high refractive index, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{H}$
\end_inset

, and for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}l_{i}=\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
|r|=\left(\frac{1-\left(\frac{n_{H}}{n_{L}}\right)^{2N}\frac{n_{H}^{2}}{n_{r}n_{l}}}{1+\left(\frac{n_{H}}{n_{L}}\right)^{2N}\frac{n_{H}^{2}}{n_{r}n_{l}}}\right)^{2}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The phase within the region of high reflectivity (the 
\emph on
stop band
\emph default
) of the reflector can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{r}=\frac{n_{c}L_{DBR}}{c}\left(\omega-\omega_{c}\right),\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{DBR}$
\end_inset

 is the penetration depth into the DBR and is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "savona_exact_1995"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{DBR}=\frac{\lambda_{c}}{2}\frac{n_{L}n_{H}}{n_{c}\left(n_{H}-n_{L}\right)}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an illustration, we present in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Sample_DBR_reflection"

\end_inset

 an exact calculation of the reflection coefficient of a DBR containing
 35 pairs of alternating high and low refractive index layers.
 The refractive indices for the simulation are 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{l}=1$
\end_inset

 (air), 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{H}=3.45$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $Al_{0.2}Ga_{0.8}As$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{L}=2.98$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $AlAs$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{r}=3.59$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $GaAs$
\end_inset

) (the structure refractive index profile is presented in (a)).
 In subplots (b) and (c) we plot the reflection coefficient as a function
 of the normalized wavelength, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{\lambda}{\lambda_{c}}$
\end_inset

, and the phase acquired by the electromagnetic field at each layer, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\frac{2\pi l_{i}n_{i}}{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The stop-band, as can be clearly seen from these plots, is centered at
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 In subplot (b) we also present the reflectivity phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{r}$
\end_inset

, where the zero-phase crossing is observed at 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

