\begin_layout Section
Microcavity Optical Characteristics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Microcavity Reflection Spectrum 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A microcavity (MC) is a Fabry-Perot resonator, whose mirrors are two DBRs
 and the spacer material is a semiconductor layer with refractive index
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}$
\end_inset

 and of length 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{c}=\frac{\lambda_{c}}{2n_{c}}m$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer).
 The microcavity can be analyzed similarly to the DBR using the transfer
 matrix formalism.
 The MC's transfer matrix for a wave traveling from left to right can be
 written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
M_{MC}=M_{DBR}^{r}M_{c}M_{DBR}^{l},\label{eq:MC_transfer_matrix_1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the transfer matrix of the spacer (cavity) layer.
 We can write the these three transfer matrices in their most general form
 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
M_{DBR}^{r} & = & \frac{n_{c}}{n_{r}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{t_{r}^{\star}} & -\frac{r_{r}^{\star}}{t_{r}^{\star}}\\
-\frac{r_{r}}{t_{r}} & \frac{1}{t_{r}}\end{array}\right),\\
M_{DBR}^{l} & = & \frac{n_{l}}{n_{c}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{t_{l}^{\star}} & \frac{r_{l}}{t_{l}}\\
\frac{r_{l}^{\star}}{t_{l}^{\star}} & \frac{1}{t_{l}}\end{array}\right),\\
M_{c} & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
e^{ikl_{c}} & 0\\
0 & e^{-ikl_{c}}\end{array}\right),\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r_{l},\, t_{l}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r_{r},\, t_{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 are, respectively, the reflection and transmission coefficients of the
 left- and right-hand DBR mirrors (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Microcavity_schematic_structure"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{r}$
\end_inset

 are the left- and right-hand cladding material refractive indices, respectively.
\end_layout

