\begin_layout Subsection
Microcavity Confined Photon
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dispersion of the MC modes is defined as the 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 dependence of the MC-mode energy.
 As we have seen in the previous section, it is obtained from the resonance
 condition 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{z}l_{eff}=m\pi$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{z}=\sqrt{\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}-k_{t}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Combining this condition with the condition for a propagating wave indside
 the cavity, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}^{2}<\frac{\omega^{2}}{c^{2}}$
\end_inset

, we can write the MC-mode dispersion relation of the form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Skolnick1998"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{ph}\left(k_{t}\right)=\frac{\hbar ck}{n_{c}}=\frac{\hbar c}{n_{c}}\sqrt{\left(\frac{2\pi m}{l_{c}}\right)^{2}+k_{t}^{2}},\label{eq:MC_Mode_Dispersion}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer.
 For small 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 we approximate the dispersion relation to a parabola 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{ph}(k_{t})\cong\frac{2\pi\hbar c}{n_{c}l_{c}}\left(1+\frac{\hbar^{2}k_{t}^{2}}{2m_{ph}}\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

The parabolic dispersion can be interpreted as a cavity photon that carries
 a very small in-plane effective mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ph}=\frac{\hbar n_{c}}{cl_{c}}\approx10^{-5}m_{0}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the free electron mass.
 
