\begin_layout Section
Microcavity Polaritons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen in previous sections, a MC is used to sort out a single
 mode of the electromagnetic field that is confined in one direction.
 Semiconductor microcavities with embedded quantum-wells (QW) are of particular
 interest as they exhibit a one-dimensional confinement of both the electronic
 states and the electromagnetic field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ducloy1996"

\end_inset

.
 The resonant transitions (excitons) in QW's behave like a two-level absorber
 system due to their enhanced oscillator strength and the large binding
 energy resulting from the quantum confinement 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Andreani1990"

\end_inset

.
 The interaction of the MC-photon with the QW-exciton leads to several new
 effects that can generally be divided into two classes: (1) the enhancement
 or inhibition of the spontaneous emission rate in the weak coupling regime
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yokoyama1990"

\end_inset

 and (2) the observation of new eigen-modes with a Rabi splitting (normal
 mode splitting) between them, in the strong coupling regime 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhu1990,Weisbuch1992"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coupled exciton-photon eigenstates of the QW embedded in a MC are called
 
\emph on
cavity polaritons
\emph default
, by analogy with the exciton-polariton modes of the bulk material 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hopfield1958"

\end_inset

.
 Various theoretical models have been proposed to describe the exciton-cavity
 polariton such as a semi-classical linear dispersion model, in which the
 active medium is represented by a Lorentzian oscillator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Savona1999,Weisbuch1992,Zhu1990"

\end_inset

, and a quantum mechanical model representing the MC-photon and the QW exciton
 as two coupled harmonic oscillators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pau1995,Skolnick1998,Girlanda1995"

\end_inset

.
 The semi-classical model has the advantage of using the realistic MC parameters
 and it gives the reflectivity, transmission and absorption spectra.
 The coupled oscillators model is more suitable for the description of the
 dynamics of the MC-polaritons.
 A full quantum mechanical treatment developed in
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Savona1995"

\end_inset

 is out of the scope of this thesis.
 In this section we elaborate on the quantum mechanical model for the two-level
 absorber and extend the analog to a microcavity polariton.
 The presented review in primarily based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rapaport2001"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Subsection
Bulk Exciton Polaritons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Polaritons are the normal modes of optically active excitons and a radiation
 field in solids 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hopfield1958"

\end_inset

.
 In other words, the polariton involves a spatially coherent coupling of
 the exciton with the optical field.
 In an infinite crystal, only those excitons at the crossing of the noninteracti
ng exciton and photon dispersions can decay, owing to to the requirement
 of energy-momentum conservation in the radiation process (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Bulk_Polarioton_Dispersion"

\end_inset

).
 However, the exciton-photon coupling leads to an anticrossing in the polariton
 dispersions.
 Thus exciton polaritons in the bulk are stationary.
 Their radiative decay must be associated with phonons, defects, impurities,
 or crystal interfaces.
 
