\begin_layout Subsection
Strong Absorber-Photon Coupling 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Single Two-level System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the interaction of a single photon mode with two-level absorber
 we employ the Jaynes-Cummings model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jaynes1962,Haroche1984,Raimond1996"

\end_inset

, where a single photon mode is described by the Fock Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{F}=\hbar\omega\left(p^{\dagger}p+\frac{1}{2}\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are, respectively, the creation and annihilation operators that connect
 different photon Fock states, defined in analogy to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Creation_Annihilation_Operations"

\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
p\left|n\right\rangle  & = & \sqrt{n}\left|n-1\right\rangle ,\\
p^{\dagger}\left|n\right\rangle  & = & \sqrt{n+1}\left|n+1\right\rangle .\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 obey the bosonic commutation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[p,p^{\dagger}\right]=1$
\end_inset

.
 The field operator of the photon field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r})=\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega}{2\epsilon_{0}V}}\left[pf\left(\mathbf{r}\right)+p^{\dagger}f\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right],\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a complex vector function that describes the polarization and relative
 amplitude of the cavity mode at the position 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

.
 The effective cavity mode volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\int\left|f\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right|^{2}d^{3}\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

.
 The atomic two-level system is described by a two-level Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{A}=\frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega\hat{\sigma}_{z},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 is a spin 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 like operator.
 We also define two additional operators 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\sigma_{+}\left|g\right\rangle  & = & \left|e\right\rangle ,\\
\sigma_{-}\left|e\right\rangle  & = & \left|g\right\rangle ,\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 represent, respectively, the ground and excited states.
 These operators obey the fermionic commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\sigma_{+},\sigma_{-}\right]=2\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 The atom-field interaction is once again the dipole interaction (as in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Particle_E_Interaction"

\end_inset

) and is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{I}=\mathbf{d}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{E}}=-\hbar\Omega f(r)\left[p\sigma_{+}+p^{\dagger}\sigma_{-}\right].\label{eq:Atom_Field_Interaction}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the electric dipole matrix element between the ground and excited states
 of the atom and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, the coupling term, is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Omega=\frac{d}{\hbar}\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega}{2\epsilon_{0}V}}.\label{eq:Rabi_Splitting_Energy}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The ground state of the entire system is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|g;0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with the atom is the ground state and the optical cavity is devoid of photons.
 At the resonance, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, and without the atom-field interaction, all the excited states of the
 entire system are grouped into 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
equidistant manifolds of 
\end_layout

\end_inset

doubly degenerate level groups (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2_Level_Absorber_Levels"

\end_inset

(a)) 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left|g;n+1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e;n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The atom-field interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{I}$
\end_inset

 couples only the doublet states 
