, the eigenstates of the system are
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|\pm,n\right\rangle =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[\left|e,n\right\rangle \mp\left|g,n+1\right\rangle \right],\end{equation}

\end_inset

constituting symmetric and anti-symmetric combinations of the uncoupled
 states.
 The eigenenergies are given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{\pm,n}=\left(n+1\right)\hbar\omega_{0}\pm\hbar\Omega f(r)\sqrt{n+1}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The double degeneracy is lifted by the interaction and the separation between
 the dressed states within each group is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\hbar\Omega f(r)\sqrt{n+1}$
\end_inset

, termed the Rabi splitting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this case the absorption or emission spectra are highly nonlinear in
 the sense that they are strongly dependent on the number of photons.
 For example, while the emission spectrum from 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

 manifold consists of only two line with an energy separation of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\hbar\Omega f\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

, the emission spectrum from 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1$
\end_inset

 manifold has four lines with different energy separation.
 In general, the dressed states of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 manifold are split by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\hbar\Omega=f\left(r\right)\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

 and the emission spectrum from the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1$
\end_inset

 excitation manifold makes a continuous transition from four separate lines
 to three lines 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mollow1969"

\end_inset

 with increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, because the two central transition lines becoming degenerate.
 This nonlinearity stems from the fermionic nature of the atomic spin operator.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now assume the initial state of the system to be
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|\psi\left(t=0\right)\right\rangle =\left|e,1\right\rangle =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[\left|+\right\rangle +\left|-\right\rangle \right].\end{equation}

\end_inset

after a finite period of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the system will be in the state 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|\psi\left(t\right)\right\rangle =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[\left|+\right\rangle e^{-iE_{+}t/\hbar}+\left|-\right\rangle e^{-iE_{-}t/\hbar}\right].\end{equation}

\end_inset

The probability that the field mode is excited and the absorber is in its
 ground state is not stationary but rather of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|\left\langle e,n\vert\psi\left(t\right)\right\rangle \right|^{2}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1+\cos\Omega t\right),\end{equation}

\end_inset

termed the Rabi oscillations.
 If the absorber is in its excited states and it emits a photon, then it
 will subsequently reabsorb the photon.
 There is no irreversible decay in this model since there is only one photon
 mode.
 In reality, the cavity damping 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 factor is finite leading to a cavity damping 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{cav}$
\end_inset

.
 In the strong coupling regime, the vacuum Rabi splitting must be greater
 than the cavity damping and the absorber damping, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\Omega>\gamma_{cav},\,\gamma_{abs}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multiple Two-Level Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An extension of the former system is a setting of multiple two level atoms
 interacting with a single photon mode.
 This system is of relevance to the semiconductor MCs, since it involves
 a large ensemble of absorbers (or QW excitations).
 We consider a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 identical two level atoms, where we assume that the atoms interact only
 through their coupling to the radiation field.
 Thus, the atomic Hamiltonian as well as the atom-field interaction are
 sums of the individual atomic Hamiltonians.
 Since all the atoms are coupled to the field in a similar fashion, the
 excitation of the atomic system is equally shared among all atoms, and
 the coupled atom-radiation system has 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

 non-degenerate, equidistant energy levels.
 This description is valid also for QWs in resonant structures since typical
 exciton size is much smaller than the optical wavelength (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\ll\lambda$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

.
 The atomic Hamiltonian and the atom-field interaction can be then expressed
 in terms of collective operators defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma_{z}=\sum_{i}\sigma_{z,i},\,\,\sigma_{+}=\sum_{i}\sigma_{+,i},\,\,\sigma_{-}=\sum_{i}\sigma_{-,i}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The atom-field interaction Hamiltonian is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{I}=\hbar\Omega\left[a\sigma_{+}+a^{\dagger}\sigma_{-}\right],\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the single atom single photon Rabi frequency, defined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Rabi_Splitting_Energy"

\end_inset

 and assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 is unity for all the atoms.
 Due to the symmetrical form of the raising and lowering operators, the
 excitation is equally shared among the atoms.
 The atomic Hamiltonian has 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

 non-degenerate levels 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|J,M\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $J=N/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-J\leq M\leq J$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two lowest states of the atomic system are the ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G\right\rangle =\left|J,-J\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the first excited state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|E\right\rangle =\left|J,-J+1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The ground state of the coupled system of atoms and cavity atoms is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G,0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, which describes an atomic ground state with an empty cavity.
 The two degenerate states in the first group under resonant condition are
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|E,0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 These two states are coupled by the atom-field interaction to form two
 dressed states exactly as for the single atom case 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|\pm,0\right\rangle =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[\left|E,0\right\rangle \mp\left|G,1\right\rangle \right].\end{equation}

\end_inset

The eigenenergies of these states are given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{\pm}=\hbar\omega_{0}\pm\hbar\Omega\sqrt{N}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The splitting energy in this case becomes larger by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

 than the isolated atom, i.e., there is an enhancement of the splitting because
 of the collective coupling of the atoms with the field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This discussion results hold only for weak light intensities, when there
 is only one photon in the cavity.
 The structure of higher dressed state groups is quite different from lowest
 state groups and thus it is different from the single atom case.
 For example, there are three equally spaced dressed levels in the second
 group, four in the third and so on.
 The spectra corresponding to these excitations are therefore very complicated.
 In the limit of very large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, it was shown 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haroche1984"

\end_inset

 that the dressed state ladder consist of levels remaining nearly equidistant
 over a large energy range, with a spacing between nearby levels being of
 the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $2m\hbar\Omega\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the photon number.
 As a result, the spectra of all the state groups will have only two distinct
 lines with an energy separation of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\hbar\Omega\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This system of many atoms where 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ll N$
\end_inset

, is similar to the dressed boson case described by the coupled oscillator
 model described in the next section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coupled Harmonic Oscillator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When two harmonic oscillators interact resonantly, the coupled system can
 be respresented by new normal modes, which are eigenstates of the total
 system Hamiltonian of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=\hbar\omega_{0}\left(a^{\dagger}a+\frac{1}{2}\right)+\hbar\omega_{0}\left(b^{\dagger}b+\frac{1}{2}\right)+\hbar\Omega\left(a^{\dagger}b+b^{\dagger}a\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here both field operators satisfy the boson commutation relation.
 As we have mentioned before, in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $N\gg1$
\end_inset

 identical atoms with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 photons (
\begin_inset Formula $m\ll N$
\end_inset

) that are resonantly coupled to a single mode, the above dressed boson
 is a valid concept.
 The coupling constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is then not the single atom Rabi frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{s}$
\end_inset

, but the enhanced 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{s}\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

 collective coupling of all the atoms.
 An exciton in a semiconductor QW is in fact similar to such an assembly
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 identical atoms, namely each lattice site having a unit dipole moment correspon
ds to a single two level atom.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dressed bosons spectrum for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 is identical to that of the corresponding dressed fermions.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $m=2$
\end_inset

 excitation state group has three degenerate bare states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|2\right\rangle _{a}\left|0\right\rangle _{b},\,\left|1\right\rangle _{a}\left|1\right\rangle _{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle _{a}\left|2\right\rangle _{b}$
\end_inset

, that split into three non-degenerate dressed states
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left|2,-\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{2}\left|2\right\rangle _{a}\left|0\right\rangle _{b}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left|1\right\rangle _{a}\left|1\right\rangle _{b}+\frac{1}{2}\left|0\right\rangle _{a}\left|2\right\rangle _{b},\\
\left|2,+\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{2}\left|2\right\rangle _{a}\left|0\right\rangle _{b}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left|1\right\rangle _{a}\left|1\right\rangle _{b}+\frac{1}{2}\left|0\right\rangle _{a}\left|2\right\rangle _{b},\\
\left|2,0\right\rangle  & = & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left|2\right\rangle _{a}\left|0\right\rangle _{b}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left|0\right\rangle _{a}\left|2\right\rangle _{b},\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

with a frequency separation of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 The emission spectrum from the 
\begin_inset Formula $m=2$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 state groups is, however, identical to that from 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

 consisting of only two separate lines.
 This is because of the six possible transitions, two are forbidden and
 two pairs are degenerate.
 In general, the emission spectrum always has only two lines irrespective
 of the excitation state group.
 The dressed boson is then a perfectly linear system.
 Note that there is no difference between the fermion and boson cases for
 the first state group, thus in order to observe the differences a very
 high light intensity must be employed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Strong Coupling in a Semiconductor Microcavity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Excitonic-Effects"

\end_inset

, the exciton states are quantized parallel to the growth direction due
 to the QW electronic confinement but, as for the photonic states, their
 in-plane motion is free with a continuum of in-plane excitonic wave vector
 states.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

As mentioned in the previous sections, excitons are similar to the two-level
 systems since only coupling between excitons and photon states of the same
 in-plane wave vector are allowed.
 This coupling mixes the exciton and the photon modes and the normal modes
 are similar to a dressed boson, and thus in analogy this modes are called
 dressed excitons.
 When this splitting is significantly greater then both the exciton and
 the cavity linewidths the system is said to be in the strong coupling regime.
 Two different models are usually used to describe such a system 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Savona1999,Savona1995,Pau1995"

\end_inset

.
 The first is a coupled quantum oscillators and the second is the semiclassical
 linear dispersion model (LDM).
 A brief summary of these two models is given and a new approach to the
 cavity polariton modeling is presented.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:MC_Coupled_Oscillator_Model"

\end_inset

Coupled Oscillator Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the coupled oscillator model, we treat both the exciton transition and
 the photon mode as two quantum harmonic oscillators that are coupled together
 via their dipole interaction.
 The simplest Hamiltonian that describes this system can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=\left(E_{X}\left(\mathbf{k}_{t}\right)+\gamma_{X}\right)b^{\dagger}b+\left(E_{C}\left(\mathbf{k}_{t}\right)+\gamma_{C}\right)a^{\dagger}a+\hbar\Omega\left(a^{\dagger}b+b^{\dagger}a\right),\label{eq:Photon_Exciton_Coupled_Oscillator_Hamiltonian}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we assume a single MC mode interacting with one electron-hole (exciton)
 mode.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{X}$
\end_inset

 is the phenomenological linewidth of the exciton and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{C}$
\end_inset

 is the cavity photon mode linewidth given by eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MC_Mode_Linewidth"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are the exciton creation and annihilation operators.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{C}\left(\mathbf{k}_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the photon in-plane dispersion inside the cavity given by eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MC_Mode_Dispersion"

\end_inset

.
 This Hamiltonian can be written in a matrix form as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
E_{X}\left(k_{t}\right)+i\gamma_{X} & \frac{\hbar\Omega}{2}\\
\frac{\hbar\Omega}{2} & E_{C}\left(k_{t}\right)+i\gamma_{C}\end{array}\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

For this simple model, the diagonalization of this Hamiltonian for each
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 gives the polariton eigenenergies
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{\pm}\left(k_{t}\right)=\frac{E_{X}\left(k_{t}\right)+E_{C}\left(k_{t}\right)}{2}\pm\sqrt{\left[E_{X}\left(k_{t}\right)-E_{C}\left(k_{t}\right)+i\left(\frac{\gamma_{X}-\gamma_{C}}{2}\right)\right]+\left(\frac{\hbar\Omega}{2}\right)^{2}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

We denote the eigenvalues of this This model can be extended to include
 larger number of exciton modes and the same single cavity mode, in which
 case the Hamiltonian matrix to be diagonalized becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $(N_{X}+1)\times(N_{X}+1)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{X}$
\end_inset

 is the number of strongly interacting excitons present in the system.
 For example, for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}-HH_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}-LH_{1}$
\end_inset

 excitons the Hamiltonian becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
E_{C}\left(k_{t}\right)+i\gamma_{C} & \frac{\hbar\Omega_{X_{LH}}}{2} & \frac{\hbar\Omega_{X_{HH}}}{2}\\
\left(\frac{\hbar\Omega_{X_{LH}}}{2}\right)^{*} & E_{X_{LH}}\left(k_{t}\right)-i\gamma_{X_{LH}} & 0\\
\left(\frac{\hbar\Omega_{X_{HH}}}{2}\right)^{*} & 0 & E_{X_{HH}}\left(k_{t}\right)+i\gamma_{X_{HH}}\end{array}\right).\label{eq:Two_Exiton_Coupled_Oscillator_Fit_Hamiltonian}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to simplify the coupled oscillator Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Photon_Exciton_Coupled_Oscillator_Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

 and present a more particle-like picture of the polariton, we apply the
 Bogoliuvob's transformation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hopfield1958"

\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{Pol}=\sum_{i}(E_{p,i}-i\gamma_{p,i})p_{i}^{\dagger}p_{i},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 are, respectively, the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th polariton branch creation and annihilation operators, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p,i}$
\end_inset

 is the eigenergy of this polariton branch and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{p,i}$
\end_inset

 is its linewidth.
 The eigenstates of this Hamiltonian can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|P_{i}\right\rangle =\left|\alpha_{C}\right|^{2}\left|C\right\rangle +\sum_{j}\left|\alpha_{i,j}\right|^{2}\left|X_{j}\right\rangle ,\label{eq:Polariton_Wavefunction}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left|C\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|X_{j}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are, respectively, the cavity mode and the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th bare exciton wavefunctions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 are the admixing coefficients of the polariton.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linear Dispersion Model and Beyond
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another description for the optical response of QW excitons inside a MC
 structure within the linear regime can be given in the framework of the
 semiclassical linear dispersion model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Savona1995,Pau1995"

\end_inset

.
 In this model, the transfer matrix formalism is used to describe the light
 propagation inside the MC layers (as explained earlier in this chapter).
 In the typical formulation of the model, the QW resonances (excitons) are
 treated as a resonant Lorentzian dispersive term in the dielectric response
 function of the QW material.
 The advantage of the LDM approach in calculating the absorption, transmission
 and reflection spectra is that it takes into account the geometry of the
 MC including all the DBR's.
 
\end_layout

